The Trevor Project: (866) 488-7386

The Trevor Project is the leading national organization providing crisis intervention and suicide prevention services to lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender and questioning (LGBTQ) young people ages 13-24.

National Suicide Prevention Lifeline: (800) 273-8255 (online chat available)

The National Suicide Prevention Lifeline is a national network of local crisis centers that provides free and confidential emotional support to people in suicidal crisis or emotional distress 24 hours a day, 7 days a week. 

Crisis Text Line: Text START to 741-741

Crisis Text Line is free, 24/7 support for those in crisis. Text from anywhere in the USA to text with a trained Crisis Counselor.

The Gay, Lesbian, Bisexual and Transgender National Hotline: (888) 843-4564
And
The GLBT National Youth Talkline (youth serving youth through age 25): (800) 246-7743

Both provide telephone, online private one-to-one chat and email peer-support, as well as factual information and local resources for cities and towns across the United States.

Trans Lifeline: (877) 565-8860

Trans Lifeline is a trans-led organization that connects trans people to the community, support, and resources they need to survive and thrive.

The National Runaway Safeline: 800-RUNAWAY (800-786-2929)

Provides advice and assistance to runaways, including resources, shelter, transportation, assistance in finding counseling, and transitioning back to home life. NRS frontline staff will also act as advocates and mediators if/as needed.

The True Colors United: (212) 461-4401

The True Colors Fund is working to end homelessness among lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, queer, and questioning youth, creating a world in which all young people can be their true selves. True Colors United runs a database of service providers.

I started my trauma therapy 5 years ago. In that time I’ve had to let go of, or put distance between, so many relationships, family, friends. All of whom don’t quite understand. Repost from @nate_postlethwait

Behind closed doors in many homes is unspeakable tragedy. The aftermath of this tragedy are innocent souls trying to find their way back to something that helps them feel safe, free. We go back home to try and open the door and realize that the only way they will let us stay, is if we keep the doors closed. To hold the stories of what we saw, what was done to us, what changed us, is not to be brought to light. So, if we stay and belong, we let the pain live free in us while letting go of hope for better days.
 
When we grow, we see it is possible to build a livable life. What it means to start taking back our time, our breath, our truth, and see how those can work together in a way that creates a new path where the pain no longer holds us captive. 

But, don’t dismiss the cost. The loss of those who would rather not see you, than see you be honest about what they have done. The ones who kept the door shut, and pretended to hold you close, to offer themselves to you, if you remained silent. 
 
The cost and loss. It troubles me how many people don’t get this. What it takes, what it means, to have no choice but to walk away from everything to heal. Then we begin to rebuild and shine and they still think our story is about them. Because their doors are shut with their lies, they do not see they are offered the same freedom. 
 
To those who had to walk away.
 
To those who know the grief and pain.
 
To those who don’t have the words.
 
May you feel warmth when you need it, assurance when you make changes, and celebration for what you have done to heal. Peace as you continue to do whatever it takes to get free.

Bullseye! (Please read Nate’s words below) The disconnect, escape, crutches, triggers, & the countless times I chased & depleted myself for family, former friends, colleagues, & exes. It has been eye opening to see how used to the previous version of me those folks became. As I heal more & more, those folks pull away.
I share this because I know so many of you are also walking this path. Every step deeper into healing brings me joy, peace, gentleness, & reunites me with the true Me.
Sending you lots of love & encouragement as you brave each step forward folks.

Repost from @nate_postlethwait
•
There is a shift that happens when someone is traumatized where they are disconnecting from their body because there is pain they don’t know how to address there. They are disconnecting from their mind because it is going to places and things that we don’t know how to address. 

Then we move through the world looking for people or things to help us either escape further because it feels like it’s all too much, or help us find our way back to ourselves. We aim to find a safe way where we learn to tenderly, compassionately, boldly love those parts of us, while shifting them away from that pain being such a present force (A reminder there is no one or right way to do this…there are many). 

Along the way we feel misunderstood, so we try to explain better because feeling misunderstood triggers that old pain. 

Along the way we feel overlooked so we try to become more pleasing because feeling overlooked triggers old pain. 

Along the way we end up trying to mold ourselves to things and people that will never be to our healing what we hope they can be and we are more tired because we’ve offered up ourselves so much. 

Please find the things that bring you peace. 

And retract a bit of your time. 

Please find the things that bring you pleasure. 

And take back a piece of your heart. 

Please trust that if you are overextended, tired, confused then do whatever you can to find a pause, a hiding space and when you are ready, begin again. 

I’m so glad you’re here…💞💞✨✨

Me at 19. Twenty eight years ago. (What a head of hair!). I found this photo while going through some storage bins. It brought back so much. At this time I was living in Canarsie and my favorite place was to sit on my roof and look out at the Manhattan skyline and dream. I was working for a nonprofit organization that used theatre to teach literacy in after school programs. I was attending Brooklyn College (before transferring to NYU) as the first in my family to go to college. That Harvard shirt was a thrift shop purchase as that was the fad of the time in the 90’s; thrift shop fashion! I was two years into my professional career as an actor. Michael, my first great love, was still alive. Willie Ninja was also still alive and mentoring me as my guardian angel. I had been a go-go dancer at a gay punk rock bar; that was short lived as it was actually incredibly boring. I had no clue what was waiting for me but I would sit on that roof and dream, dream, dream. Seeing this again reminded me why I chose this path in the first place. I was already using my art to create change. I knew my art needed to be purposeful. Not just entertaining. Manhattan was like the Emerald City to me; it felt unreachable. All of it felt impossible. Yet here I am, on the other side looking back at this young artist feeling so proud of all he has accomplished, survived, and become. Not at all a perfect journey, thank goodness, but so beautiful. 
All you folks out there pursuing your dreams, keep going, don’t give up, the path is not linear and will never look like you dreamed it would, but keep going. Your voice and your light are always needed.
Much love folks.
#art #artist #journey #endurance #persistence #shineyourlight

After four long years, Staley v Gilead has finally gone to trial. Over a hundred prospective jurors (pictured below) filed into a federal courtroom this morning in San Francisco, and after hours of questioning, a jury of nine remains. 

It's been a wild couple of weeks. At his final pre-trial conference with all the parties (60+ lawyers on a Zoom), Senior District Judge Edward M. Chen ordered that decision makers (not just lawyers) from all parties involved be on the call, then excoriated them for not settling the case before trial.

Kenneth Feinberg has been trying to mediate a settlement. Yes, that Ken Feinberg, special master of the 9/11 Victim Compensation Fund, and administrator of the BP Deepwater Horizon Disaster Victim Compensation Fund. Rumor has it that Gilead is driving him nuts.

Kenneth, AIDS activists feel your pain.

The case is now so complicated that Judge Chen broke it into two trials. Today's jury will be deciding if Gilead struck a deal with Teva Pharmaceuticals to keep generic Truvada off the market for a few years. Repost from @nate_postlethwait When you experience any type of trauma, everything in you (focus, mind, body, nervous system) centers on that pain. That focus has an exhausting grind to it.
When there is not proper support, or resources, or hope, that can become the heavy force that shapes the way we see everything.
Is that wrong? No, it’s survival mode. Is it permanent? No, we do have *some* choice in that (takes time).
Step 1: Swap out judgment for observation (with compassion!):
-Instead of “I am unlovable.”   Try   “What has happened to make me believe I am unlovable.”
Step 2: Do something that the younger version of you loved at that time they got hurt to show them what they love matters. Let those hobbies, passions, etc become part of a greater routine on an ongoing basis. (example: anything that felt safe then, or drew you out)
Step 3: Let that younger you feel the compliments from others. See innocence in them and as an adult, acknowledge that when genuine people offer kind words, there is nothing attached. It is their observation. Imagine those words going straight to that young child who needed to hear them. Imagine being the person who says “I am going to allow my walls to come down a bit and I am going to trust that when a genuine person reflects good they see in me, I am going to trust that to sit on the surface a minute, and then let it trickle down to that younger version of me whose life would have changed drastically, if the had someone expressing that kindness earlier on.”
Imagine being the person who facilitates that.
If you do not have the support you need, take one small step towards that today, and trust it is bumpy, confusing, vulnerable (all the things), but there are so many incredible people who speak a similar language because they know a similar pain.
I have put a resource guide together with many options on how to find the support that works for you. It is a free guide (A Survivors Guide to Trauma Recovery) @ link in bio. There is also a free inner child journaling guide.

The NYPD is currently investigating multiple alleged acts of vandalism that resulted in the destruction of Pride flags at the Stonewall National Monument in Manhattan.

The most recent incident happened on June 18. Police were called to the scene around 8:00 am to discover that 33 LGBTQIA+ Pride flags, which were originally attached to the Stonewall National Monument's fence, had been broken and tossed on the ground. 

Similar incidents also occurred on June 9 and June 15. However, no arrests have been made, and it's not clear if the incidents are connected. The NYPD’s Hate Crimes Task Force is currently conducting an investigation.

Steven Menendez, a park volunteer who created the Pride flag display, told Gothamist that in the display's 6-year history, this is the first time he's seen this kind of vandalism.

‘It's kind of a statement about the climate right now towards the LGBTQ community with all the hateful political rhetoric that's going on attacking the drag and trans communities especially,’ Menendez said after the June 10 incident. 

‘I just hope that there can be more surveillance and at nighttime, better lighting around the park to keep this particular area, which is kind of the heart and soul of the LGBTQ movement, as safe as possible,’ Menendez said on June 19. ‘This neighborhood, especially during pride, should be well protected.’

I also feel profoundly encouraged and inspired to continue doing as I have always done and stand my ground, fight back unapologetically when necessary, and use my platform and my voice as an openly Gay, openly HIV Positive, Latiné human being, to leave this world, hopefully, just a tiny bit better than how it was when I was born into it.

And
The GLBT National Youth Talkline (youth serving youth through age 25): (800) 246-7743

Both provide telephone, online private one-to-one chat and email peer-support, as well as factual information and local resources for cities and towns across the United States.

Trans Lifeline: (877) 565-8860

Trans Lifeline is a trans-led organization that connects trans people to the community, support, and resources they need to survive and thrive.

The National Runaway Safeline: 800-RUNAWAY (800-786-2929)

Provides advice and assistance to runaways, including resources, shelter, transportation, assistance in finding counseling, and transitioning back to home life. NRS frontline staff will also act as advocates and mediators if/as needed.

The True Colors United: (212) 461-4401

The True Colors Fund is working to end homelessness among lesbian, gay, bisexual, transgender, queer, and questioning youth, creating a world in which all young people can be their true selves. True Colors United runs a database of service providers.
